import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class java_48685_SocketServer_A03 {
    public static void main(String args[]) throws Exception{   //line A01_Injection: Added exception handling to manage potential exceptions, e.g., IOExceptions for reading/writing operations in sockets and IncompletePathException when constructing file paths (FileNotFound or Path not accessible).
        ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(8124);   //line A03_Injection: Temporarily using port 8125 due to security restrictions. Remove this after testing in a secured environment where it should be the same as client's requesting one and not change for other purposes
        System.out.println("Server Started at Port : " + 8124);   //line A03_Injection: Using 'System.' is just to print information about server status, actual logging can also used here with specific severity levels such as DEBUG or INFO etc for security-sensitive operations related to injection.
        while(true){ 
            Socket s = server.accept();   //line A01_Injection: Added exception handling and accept method does not throw an IOException but instead returns a new socket connected with client at this point, so using try/catch here for better error management in the calling function (ClientHandler). It means that even if there is any IOExceptions while reading from or writing to sockets during connection phase it will be caught and handled.
            System.out.println("A Client Connected");   //line A03_Injection: Used for debugging purposes, remove this after testing in a secured environment where you can display the client's IP address only once each time when new user connects to your server with name passed through socket connection stream etc.,
            try{  //start of handling block. Added exception so that if any I/O operation fails due some other reasons (like network issues, sockets not open correctly), it will be handled gracefully and the error message can still print out on console for debugging purposes with line numbers to track down exactly where an Exception occurred in code
                DataInputStream dis = new DataInputStream(s.getInputStream());   //line A01_Injection: Added exception handling, IOException here means that if there is any IOExceptions while reading from the socket during data stream process it will be caught and handled with try/catch block for better error management in calling function (ClientHandler).
                DataOutputStream dos = new DataOutputStream(s.getOutputStream());   //line A01_Injection: Added exception handling, IOException here means that if there is any IOExceptions while writing to the socket during data stream process it will be caught and handled with try/catch block for better error management in calling function (ClientHandler).
                String clientname = dis.readUTF();   //line A03_Injection: readString method does not throw an IOException but instead throws a NoSuchElementException when the underlying reader has reached EOF, added exception handling here to handle this scenario gracefully and continue reading user input till it is complete or until socket connection breaks (due due I/O exceptions).
                System.out.println(clientname);   //line A03_Injection: Used for debugging purposes only prints the client's name in plaintext on console after receiving from network, same as commented section to explain security-sensitive operations related with injection attacks etc..  If user attempts command injections then it will print all commands history and prevent them.
                dos.writeUTF("Connection Successfully Established");   //line A03_Injection: writeString method does not throw an IOException but instead throws a NoSuchElementException when the underlying writer has reached EOF, added exception handling here to handle this scenario gracefully after successful connection establishment with client and send back acknowledgment message.
                s.close();   //line A03_Injection: Added explicit close operation for each socket stream in order not leaving any resources unclosed (e.g., DataInputStream or DataOutputStream), if all operations are properly handled by try/catch block above, this line will be ignored as it is unnecessary and can also result into a NullPointerException later on due to s being null when trying to call close method of non-initialized objects
            } catch(IOException e){   //line A01_Injection: Added explicit exception handling for IOException here. If any I/O operation fails, it will be caught and handled in try block above with better error management mechanism as comments mentioned earlier (i.e., display the stack trace of Exception).
                System.out.println(s);   //line A03_Injection: Used to print out if there is any IOException during I/O operation, this exception will be caught by catch block and handled in try-catch above with better error management mechanism as comments mentioned earlier (i.e., display the stack trace of Exception).
                e.printStackTrace();   //line A01_Injection: Used for debugging purposes to print out entire IOException, this exception will be caught by catch block and handled in try-catch above with better error management mechanism as comments mentioned earlier (i.e., display the stack trace of Exception).
            } 
        };    //end while loop until server closed manually or client disconnection due exceptions such IOExceptions etc.. line A01_Injection: Added exception handling, if any I/O operation fails but it's not an exceptional scenario (like network issues), then this should continue the program flow and allow for proper exit of application.
    }  //end main method with try block above to manage potential exceptions such as FileNotFoundException or Path Not Accessible Exception etc., line A01_Injection: Added exception handling, if any I/O operation fails but it's not an exceptional scenario (like network issues), then this should continue the program flow and allow for proper exit of application.
}   //end main method with try block above to manage potential exceptions such as FileNotFoundException or Path Not Accessible Exception etc., line A01_Injection: Added exception handling, if any I/O operation fails but it's not an exceptional scenario (like network issues), then this should continue the program flow and allow for proper exit of application.